-- LLM evaluation:

  yield findings ≡ "Tokyo's ramen landscape divides into four major styles: (1) Tonkotsu — rich pork bone broth, thinner noodles. Best examples: Fuunji (tsukemen variant, Shinjuku, 20-40 min queue), Ichiran (Shibuya, solo booth experience, no queue management). (2) Shoyu — soy-sauce based, clear broth. Classic Tokyo style. Ippudo has shops everywhere but the original experience is at smaller independents. (3) Miso — heavier, northern-influenced. Menya Musashi in Shinjuku does a rich miso. (4) Tsukemen — dipping noodles. Fuunji (Shinjuku) and Rokurinsha (Tokyo Station) are the gold standard. Key constraints: most top shops are cash-only, close by 9-10 PM, queues peak 11:30-13:00 and 18:00-19:30. Going at 11:00 AM or 14:00 avoids the worst waits. Ichiran and chain shops accept IC cards; independents almost never do."

  yield recommendations ≡ [
    "Fuunji (Shinjuku, south exit): Tsukemen. Go at 11 AM to beat queue. Cash only. ¥850-1100. Closed Sundays — PLAN AROUND THIS.",
    "Afuri (Harajuku/Roppongi): Light yuzu-shio ramen, atypical and memorable. Good for someone who wants variety. Open late. Cash/card. ¥950-1200.",
    "Rokurinsha (Tokyo Station Ramen Street): Tsukemen. Accessible from any JR line. Queue typically 15-30 min. Cash only. ¥900-1100.",
    "Menya Musashi (Shinjuku): Rich miso tonkotsu. Cash only. ¥900-1000. Near Fuunji — can choose based on queue length.",
    "Ichiran (Shibuya/Shinjuku): Solo booth tonkotsu. No queue stress. IC card accepted. ¥890. Reliable 24-hour operation — good backup if plans shift late."
  ]

