    ═══════════════════════════════════════════════
    TOKYO WEEKEND: RAMEN & ARCHITECTURE
    Budget: ~¥15,000/person ($100 USD)
    ═══════════════════════════════════════════════

    BEFORE YOU GO
    ─────────────
    • Bring ¥10,000 cash (most ramen shops are cash-only)
    • Buy SUICA IC card at any JR station, load ¥3,000
    • Book Shibuya Sky observation deck online (¥2,000)
    • Download Google Maps offline for Tokyo (transit directions work offline)

    DAY 1 (SATURDAY) — EAST TOKYO: Temples, Museums & Lamb
    ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

    🏛 07:00  SENSO-JI TEMPLE, Asakusa
              Tokyo's oldest temple (645 AD). Massive red lantern gate (Kaminarimon),
              five-story pagoda, incense hall. Arrive early — by 10 AM it's packed.
              Walk Nakamise-dori afterward for street snacks.
              Free | Always open | 45 min

    🏛 09:30  → Metro Ginza line to Ueno (5 min)

    🏛 10:00  NATIONAL MUSEUM OF WESTERN ART, Ueno
              Le Corbusier's only building in East Asia. UNESCO World Heritage.
              Pilotis entrance, spiral interior gallery, rooftop garden.
              ¥500 cash/IC | Open 9:30-17:30 Sat | 60 min

    🍜 11:30  MENSHO TOKYO (8 min walk, Taito-ku 3-2-4)
              Lamb bone ramen — rich, unusual, unforgettable. The backstreet
              location feels like old-town Tokyo. Counter seats only.
              ¥1,100-1,400 cash | Open 11:00-15:00 | 30 min
              Backup: Tetsu Ramen inside Atre Ueno station (tsukemen, ¥900)

    🏛 12:30  → Metro Hibiya line to Roppongi (25 min)

    🏛 13:00  21_21 DESIGN SIGHT, Roppongi
              Tadao Ando's sunken concrete gallery — mostly underground,
              natural light through angular skylights. Current exhibition rotates.
              Architecture + art in one visit.
              ¥1,200 cash/CC | Open 10:00-19:00 | 60-90 min

    🏛 15:00  ROPPONGI HILLS WALK
              National Art Center exterior (Kurokawa's undulating glass facade).
              Mori Tower observation free areas. Tokyo Tower viewpoint.
              Free | 45 min

    🍜 17:30  AFURI, Roppongi
              Yuzu shio (citrus salt) ramen — light, fragrant, refreshing.
              Perfect counterpoint after a day of heavy architecture.
              ¥950-1,200 cash/IC | Open until 23:00 | 30 min

    🌃 19:00  Evening free. Roppongi nightlife or return to hotel.


    DAY 2 (SUNDAY) — WEST TOKYO: Shrines, Starchitects & Tonkotsu
    ────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────

    🏛 07:30  MEIJI SHRINE, Harajuku
              The architecture IS the forest — 100-year-old designed woodland
              leading to the shrine. Giant torii gates, gravel meditation paths.
              Shinto spatial design at its finest.
              Free | Opens at sunrise | 30-45 min

    ☕ 09:00  Walk to Omotesando. Coffee at Omotesando Koffee or Blue Bottle.

    🏛 09:30  OMOTESANDO ARCHITECTURE WALK
              Tokyo's starchitect row, all within a 10-minute stroll:
              • Prada Aoyama — Herzog & de Meuron's diamond-grid glass
              • Tod's — Toyo Ito's branching concrete tree facade
              • Dior — SANAA's translucent acrylic layers
              • Omotesando Hills — Ando's spiral ramp mall
              Free exteriors | 60 min

    🍜 11:00  AFURI, Harajuku
              Second yuzu shio if you loved yesterday's. Or walk 10 min
              to Cat Street for indie ramen alternatives.
              ¥950-1,200 cash/IC | 30 min

    🏛 12:00  → JR to Shinjuku (5 min)

    🏛 12:30  NATIONAL STADIUM EXTERIOR
              Kengo Kuma's timber-and-steel lattice for the 2020 Olympics.
              Largest wooden structure built in the modern era. Walk the
              perimeter for the full effect.
              Free | Exterior always visible | 15 min

    🍜 13:30  MENYA MUSASHI, Shinjuku (Kabukicho side, 7 min from south exit)
              Rich miso-tonkotsu — thick, hearty, deeply savory.
              Open Sundays 11:00-22:30. The definitive Day 2 bowl.
              ¥900-1,000 cash | 30 min

    🌿 15:00  SHINJUKU GYOEN (optional)
              Meiji-era gardens. Greenhouse is a minor architectural gem.
              ¥500 cash | Closes 16:30

    🏛 16:30  → JR to Shibuya (5 min)

    🏛 17:00  SHIBUYA SKY observation deck (230m)
              Open-air rooftop with city panorama. Watch the crossing from above.
              ¥2,000 CC (pre-booked) | 45 min

    🍜 18:30  ICHIRAN, Shibuya
              Solo-booth tonkotsu. Customizable richness, noodle firmness,
              garlic level. 24-hour operation — the reliable closer.
              ¥890 IC card | 30 min

    🌃 20:00  Shibuya nightlife or return to hotel.


    RAIN PLAN
    ─────────
    Swap outdoor walks for TeamLab Borderless at Azabudai Hills
    (Toranomon, ¥3,800, book ahead). Indoor architecture: 21_21,
    National Museum of Western Art, and Omotesando Hills are all
    weather-proof. Ramen shops are inherently rain-proof.

    RAMEN SCORECARD: 5 shops × 4 styles
    ─────────────────────────────────────
    Mensho Tokyo (lamb) → Afuri (yuzu shio) → Afuri (yuzu shio)
    → Menya Musashi (miso-tonkotsu) → Ichiran (tonkotsu)

    ARCHITECTURE SCORECARD: 7+ sites × 5 centuries
    ────────────────────────────────────────────────
    Senso-ji (645) → Le Corbusier (1959) → Ando (2007) →
    Meiji (1920) → Omotesando row (2000s) → Kuma (2019) → Shibuya Sky (2019)
  "

  yield meta-summary ≡ "BOOTSTRAPPING PROCESS REFLECTION: Started from zero domain cells. analyze-needs spawned 4 specialist cells (ramen, architecture, logistics, neighborhood mapping). First synthesis scored 5/10 — three specific gaps identified (vague Ueno lunch, no budget, Sunday closure conflict). spawn-gap-fillers created 3 targeted cells. Re-synthesis incorporated all patches: Mensho Tokyo for Ueno, ¥15,000 budget breakdown, Menya Musashi confirmed for Sundays. Second evaluation scored 8/10 — converged. Total cell count: 4 specialist + 3 gap-filler = 7 spawned cells from nothing. Quality trajectory: 5 → 8 in one gap-fill iteration. Key insight: the first synthesis was 80% of the way there — gap-fillers did PRECISION work (specific shop names, hours, prices) rather than BREADTH work. This suggests bootstrapping from zero works best when the initial specialist wave is broad and the gap-fill wave is narrow. The guard clause (v0.2) correctly prevented a second round of gap-filling when the plan reached quality threshold — no wasted computation."

